# Global instructions for all projects

## Source control

You will typically be operating from within a Jujutsu (`jj`) worktree.
Use `jj` for all source control operations.
You should never need to invoke `git`.
If you feel you are in a situation where you _do_ need to invoke `git` directly,
confirm with me first.

**Never** make edits to the working copy without creating your own jj revision
to hold those edits.
Similarly, **never** use `jj edit` to edit an existing revision.
If you do, jj's aggressive snapshotting can cause local bookmarks
to diverge needlessly from their remote counterparts.
Instead, always create a new revision to hold your edits.
Use `jj describe` to describe what you are trying to accomplish with each revision.
Prefix your revision descriptions with `[π]` so they are easy to see in the log.

When creating a new revision, always use some variant of `jj new`.

You will typically want downstream revisions
to incorporate any edits you are about to make.
In this case, use `jj new -A @` to create a new revision on top of the current one,
and to rebase all downstream revisions onto the newly created one.

If you are creating a throwaway revision
that downstream revisions should _not_ incorporate,
use `jj new`.

When viewing diffs,
use `jj diff --git` for git-style code diffs,
or `jj diff --stat` for summary diffs.
I use a custom diff renderer, which means plain `jj diff` will be misleading.

## PLAN.md

When working on a feature, you will typically write an overview and detailed
plan into a file called `PLAN.md`, stored in the repo. The file must include all
relevant detail that you have learned. I will often use the file as a handoff
document, allowing multiple agents to (sequentially) make progress on the plan.

Your proposed plan should have detailed steps, which should typically be
performed in order. (Larger changes might have phases or steps that can proceed
independently. Always use the plan document as the ground truth for ordering and
dependencies between steps.) The plan should have status markers to clearly
indicate which steps and phases have already been completed. When resuming a
plan that a previous agent created, read through other files in the repo as
necessary to validate that the status markers are accurate. You should include
these instructions in the plan even though they are also listed here in this
AGENTS.md file.
